post_text: It was such a great day welcoming our first round of Spartans back for the 2020-2021 school year yesterday. Being reunited with our students in person or virtually, it was a day filled with excitement, reconnection, and navigating new experiences together. Certainly these coming days and weeks will be a learning experience for all of us, but we are excited to move forward as a Spartan team. We wish all of our Spartans the best of luck this school year, and are excited to see even more of you in person this Thursday. Have a great Spartan day!

post_text:
Wyomissing Area students and teachers have continued to bring beautiful artwork to our community into the summer months. Included here are photos of the mural installations that occurred over the past couple weeks. Both projects were designed and fabricated by the Wyomissing Area Public Art Workshop and were funded in part by WAEF.

Arabesque (the Blue Mural), is located behind Baldwin Brass in the 600 block of Court Street. It was designed with Suzanne Fellows as lead artist. Spartans Steven and Jamair both helped with the lift installation.

The second mural (not yet named), is located at 645 Court Street, and will have an additional element added in the next couple weeks and we look forward to sharing that with you. Well done Spartans and thank you Mr. Miller for your wonderful leadership in providing these opportunities to our students and for our community.

post_text:
📚Attention Spartans! We’re excited to announce a free, virtual summer tutoring program for students entering grades 1 through 4! The program will consist of one-on-one sessions led by high school students and personalized to each student’s academic needs. Tutors and elementary students will meet remotely twice a week for five weeks, beginning July 6th and ending August 7th. The curriculum will cover math and reading topics in addition to addressing the emotional concerns of young students experiencing social isolation during the Covid-19 pandemic. If you feel that your child would benefit from this experience, please register using the link in the comments or email Elizabeth Harenza at 204265@students.wyoarea.org with any questions. Registration ends July 3rd.

*If you are a 9th-12th grade student interesting in volunteering to be a tutor, contact Elizabeth Harenza at the email listed above.*

post_text: Mrs. Easteadt challenged her SPARK students in grades 5 and 6 to create independent projects that would impact their school or local community. Maddie Olivard, 6th grade, created positive messages to go on bathroom stalls in each of the student bathrooms at WREC. At the advice of Mr. Mike Miller, art teacher at WREC, she used vinyl and her Cricut machine at home to create the messages. She wrote a grant to the PTA, but with the school closure, wasn't able to submit it. PTA President Megan Lynch graciously approved her supply cost through emails and had the vinyl delivered right to Maddie’s house. Maddie created the following messages (in addition to others) and has plans to display them as soon as we are able to return to WREC. Amazing work, Maddie. These positive messages will be a great addition to WREC.

post_text: At the JSHS, students in Mr. Krick’s Theatre Arts class were tasked with creating a video blog from the perspective of someone who’s been impacted by COVID-19. Students began with a character development worksheet to help craft the details of their character, then submitted multiple drafts of their script – noting elements such as scenery, costumes, hair/make-up, and emotions before ultimately filming and submitting their final project. Exceptional final submissions included those of DreLina Booth ’22 and Sam Arentz ’21.

post_text: The Eggernaut Egg Drop is one of WREC’s most long-standing projects. This year, instead of dropping coffee-can space capsules from the roof of the school, students could use a variety of supplies found at home to create their space capsule. The goal is to protect an egg from a high fall. Many students got the whole family involved: someone to launch, someone to film, and many spectators participated in this at-home project which encouraged creativity and togetherness. Thank you Mrs. Kupiszewski for sharing this story with us!

post_text: This year’s Academic Awards for grades 7-12 are available to view. Families of recipients will receive an email link to the awards from the Guidance Office. Special recognition, appreciation, and thanks go to Mrs. Amber Gockley for coordinating and developing this year’s online award ceremonies. Aided by Mrs. Luppold for the seventh and eighth grade ceremonies, Mrs. Gockley was an exceptional leader in developing a method in which to recognize our 7-12 students for their achievements. Thank you for your hard work and dedication to the Wyomissing Area JSHS Community, and congratulations to the award recipients.

post_text: Congratulations, Max! This is a fantastic accomplishment and you are a wonderful example for future Spartans. We can’t wait to see what is next for you at Colgate.
shared_text:
Spotlight On Berks Sports
May 16 at 11:00 PM ·

SPOTLIGHT ON BERKS SPORTS is proud to announce the first ever winner of the BCIAA Male Athlete of the Year

Max Hurleman
Wyomissing

Max is a four sport athlete, excelling in football, basketball, lacrosse, and track & field. On the football field, he was a four year starter and captain, who helped lead the Spartans to the District III 3A championship as a senior. During his final season, Max rushed for 1,238 yards (9.2 yards per carry), had 215 receiving yards (14.3 yards per reception), and scored 20 total touchdowns. For his effort, Max was selected as BCIAA Offensive Back of the Year in Division 2, All-State, and All-American. In his senior basketball season, Max led the Spartans to their first winning season since 2017. He averaged 14.9 points per game, and made 39 three point shots. That performance helped get him selected to the BCIAA All-Conference Team. Max will continue his education and football career at Colgate University.
text:
Congratulations, Max! This is a fantastic accomplishment and you are a wonderful example for future Spartans. We can’t wait to see what is next for you at Colgate.

post_text: Good Morning Spartans! We love mornings that can be started sharing good news and heartwarming stories. Yesterday, Wyomissing Area teachers Mrs. Dawn Weidner and Mrs. Sue Wojciechowski were able to make deliveries to the Reading Hospital and to Manor Care thanks to the kind, generous, caring hearts of over 60 WASD employees and their donations to the WASD Gives Back Campaign. With the help of Chatty Monks Brewing Company, and the baking expertise of Gourmand Café, they were able to provide 100 meals with dessert to the Facilities Crew at Tower Health. Additionally, they were able to send cupcakes to the workers at Manor Care in West Reading. We are so proud of the employees in the Wyomissing Area School District and we support those who are working on the front lines of this pandemic. Thank you to Mrs. Weidner and Mrs. Wojciechowski for organizing this act of support and kindness. Thank you to all who donated, and thank you to Chatty Monks Brewing Company and Gourmand Café for providing this opportunity. These are the things that make this community such a wonderful place.

post_text:
It’s Teacher Appreciation Week! We know our teachers would love to spend this week at school with their students, but just as they have always shown their ability to be creative, to be flexible, to think outside the box, to uphold excellence, and to go above and beyond for our students, that is certainly true during these unique times. We would like to make a special effort during Teacher Appreciation Week to pause and really show our love for the teachers in our lives. We encourage you to comment below, or reach out directly, to tell your teacher how much you…

- Love (❤️) how they encourage you in special ways,
- Like (👍) what’s happening in their virtual classroom
- Celebrate (🎉) their achievements with students
- Care about (😍) their commitment to students and families

Use these emojis and more and get creative! Thank you for always supporting our teachers, and thank you teachers for all you do. Happy Teacher Appreciation Week!

post_text:
Hey Spartans! It’s time to “Get Your Walk On!”

👣👟

The Health & PE Teachers of Berks County want to give you some motivation to get active! Secondary H&PE teachers in Berks County and the BCIU have joined together to form a Walking Challenge among all Secondary Students in Berks County, PA. This voluntary, individual fitness initiative starts on May 1 and runs until May 29. As always, we encourage you to get in the recommended 10,000 steps a day, but this challenge offers a little motivation to help you achieve that recommendation! The STRAVA app will be used to provide updates on individual progress.

The link to join and info on the STRAVA app are posted in the comments.

Good Luck!

post_text: Through our virtual classes, teachers and classmates have gotten to stay connected with each other, say hello to many parents, and meet siblings and pets too! But, our students are not the only ones who enjoy sharing their pets at WebEx meetings! Many members of our staff at WREC celebrated hard work and milestone occasions by adding lifelong fur friends to their families in recent weeks, and took turns introducing Cookie, Winnie, Bravo, and Teddy to the rest of the Spartan family. These new four-legged family members have certainly brought some joy to their new families during this time of distance learning 🐾

post_text: Mrs. Bogert and her biology class reviewed the concept of Evolution, which is what they have been learning about remotely during this period of distance learning, through a collaborative Kahoot! They enjoyed the fun community aspect, and as a teacher, Mrs. Bogert was able to get some instant feedback on areas of confusion. She said “it was easy to use their responses to then address misconceptions or areas of confusion and then quickly explain the concept while live. It gave me that "feel" of responding to the needs of the class without actually being together.” Well done to these Spartans for finding creative ways to collaborate as a class.

post_text: Students in Honors Chemistry recently began a unit on solubility. They were provided with the option to complete an at-home chromatography experiment to apply their new learning despite the distance. This analytical tool is used in research and industry to separate components of a mixture. Students investigated the properties of solutes, solvents, and solubility while separating permanent marker dyes on recycled t-shirts.

post_text:
Happy National Student Athlete day to all of our student athletes. We are proud of each of you for your efforts!

Here are a few athlete highlights:

🌟 Before the school closings, Hannah Hurleman competed in the PIAA State Championship for swimming, earning a 5th place finish in the 50 free and a 7th place finish in the 100 free. Congratulations Hannah!

🌟We know many of our spring athletes are disappointed to not be participating in their seasons so far this year. The Reading Eagle wrote a few feature articles on our track team and a few Spartan athletes who hope to return to the track this Spring. Links to those articles are in the comments.

🌟Additionally in the comments, you’ll find a link to an article about Spartan Jevin Tranquillo.

We are thinking of all of our student athletes today, and hope to see you back in action soon!

Good Morning Spartans! As we move into week 2 of online instruction, we want to be sure to keep our sense of community alive. Today we are introducing “Monday Morning Announcements.” Students can access the announcement clip every Monday through Class Dojo, on their class Schoology page, and on social media. If you’re interested in submitting a “joke of the day” to be featured in an upcoming edition of the announcements, visit the link on Class Dojo or Schoology to upload your video.

Have a great Spartan day! #wasdcommunity

‼️📚✏️Attention Schoology Users!

Schoology is our Learning Management System (LMS) for grades 5-12. If your Schoology account is experiencing delays or you are having trouble accessing materials, don’t panic. Due to the high volume of students using the site across the United States for virtual education, the performance of the site has been impacted and some delays are expected.

You can check the status of Schoology at the link below.

https://status.schoology.com/

Teachers are aware of the difficulties and frustration this may cause and they understand! Do your best to keep up with assignments and communicate with teachers should you experience difficulties where deadlines are concerned. We are all flexible and will work through these challenges together.

post_text: Happy Monday Spartans! We hope your “first” day of distance learning went well. There are sure to be learning experiences along the way, so we appreciate your patience and willingness to learn with us through this process. As we move into developing our “normal” for now, it is important to recognize the hard work of many individuals across the district for all they have done to help make this transition a success and to support our students, families, and staff as we navigate this experience. From providing meals, deploying technology, meeting remotely to discuss instruction in this new way, and more, our staff members have been working very hard to uphold Spartan excellence. We are so thankful for them, and for the support of the community. We are Spartans and we are in this together.

🥪🍎Attention Spartans! The included image has updates regarding grab-and-go meal dates during the school closure.

Please note:

These meals are free for students. Meals can be picked up between 11:00 am and 12:30 pm. Children must be present to pick up the meals at the following locations:

Junior Senior High School – Main entrance by the flag pole (Cambridge Ave. entrance)
West Reading Elementary Center – Main entrance (S. 4th Ave)
Wyomissing Hills Elementary Center – Main entrance (bus drop off area)

Please do not hesitate to contact Dariely Marrero, Food Services Director, by email, dmarrero@wyoarea.org or by phone at 610-374-0739 x1118 if there are any questions or if further information is needed.

Starting Monday, April 13, we will continue to provide meals on Mondays and Wednesdays from 11:00 am – 12:30 pm through any school closure extensions communicated by Governor Wolf.

‼️SAT Update‼️

The SAT scheduled for March 14, 2020 at Wyomissing Area High School has been canceled. The approved College Board make-up date for this test administration is Saturday, March 28, 2020. All students who were registered for the March 14th test administration should receive an e-mail from College Board detailing the registration and date change and any steps the student would need to take. Students who are unable to test on the make-up date of March 28th should contact College Board Customer Service at 1-866-756-7346 for additional assistance.

post_text: The JSHS Model UN Club has been active this week. Delegates participated in a regional conference at Methacton High School on Saturday, with 5 delegates winning accolades. Today, members of the club participated in this year’s Academic World Quest competition sponsored by the World Affairs Council of Greater Reading, competing against schools across the county. This event provides students the opportunity to demonstrate their knowledge of current events and other historical topics selected by the committee. Thank you to the students for their effort and preparation for these events, and to advisors Ms. Tierney and Mr. Winson for their leadership of the club.

post_text:
Third grade completed in a friendly competition called February Fact Frenzy. All Month long they focused on getting better with their multiplication and division facts. Each week, third grade classes competed to see which class got the most facts correct on weekly timings. The students completed at total of 130,496 correct problems for the month. Everyone did a great job and worked hard to improve their fact knowledge from one week to the next.

On the last day of February, 64 third grade students competed in the February Fact Frenzy Finale. Nehzion Carter was the fastest fact caller and over-all champion for third grade. Great Job Nehzion!

post_text:
Wyomissing Area will be participating in the Canstructure event at the Berkshire Mall from Saturday March 7 through Friday March 13.
Structure building will take place from 8-12:00 tomorrow. Many county schools have entered and will be displaying their creations according to the theme of Inspire Kindness. There are Fan Favorite Tickets available from 10-1:00 if you would like to vote for your favorite structures.

All food will be donated to Helping Harvest (formerly Berks Food Bank). The Reading Youth Volunteer Corps is organizing this event and it is sponsored by Performance Toyota. There is a Text-to-Give number if you want to support the YVC to support service learning in our communities. Text “inspire kindness” to 44-321.

If you are interested in donating your time, they will need lots of help taking apart all the displays to load cans bound for Helping Harvest on Saturday, March 14 from 7am-9am.

Thank you to the students and advisors who are participating in this special event and giving back to our community.

post_text: The PTA, in partnership with WREC and WHEC, is proud to announce the annual Walk with WYO fundraiser has begun! As the PTA's largest fundraiser, all of the money raised will directly benefit students in each of the three buildings. Students from K-6 will be collecting donations and they have the opportunity to win different levels of prize packages based on how much they raise. The goal of the PTA is 100% participation in this fun fundraiser. WHEC students will take a walk around the school property through themed decorations and activities on May 15, and on May 29, WREC students will take part in a color run/walk around the track at the West Reading Playground and enjoy a dance party. Be sure to check the PTA's website for opportunities to donate online soon! Thank you for your support!

post_text: Hannah Hurleman had a successful performance in this past weekend’s district meet, placing 2nd in the 50 free with a lifetime best time of 23.57. She was a member of the 200 free relay that placed 6th. In the 100 free, she placed 3rd with a second lifetime best time of 51.46 and was a member of the 400 free relay that placed 3rd. Hannah will be advancing to the state championship meet in the 50 free, 100 free, and 400 free relay at Bucknell University on March 11th and 12th. Congratulations Hannah. We are proud of you!

Congratulations to the following students for earning special recognition at the Berks County IU Art Show currently being held at the Goggleworks in Reading:

Senior, Kylee Loeb, earned 2nd in Printmaking

Senior, Lily Harris, earned 1st in Mixed Media/Collage

Junior, Emmerson Piacine, earned 2nd in Design

Senior, Kylee Loeb, earned an Honorable Mention in Design

Senior, Cierra Ponton, earned 3rd in Sculpture

Sophomore, Maurely Vanderpool-Estevez, earned 3rd in the NOTA/Mosaics

and…

Senior, Kylee Loeb, had a piece chosen for Berks Fast Art Digital Billboard Competition

We had 35 student artists represented at the show. In total, there are an impressive 1731 artworks from 1,100 students from all of our Berks County high schools. The exhibit is open 9am-9pm daily until March 10 at the Goggleworks.

Congratulations again to all of the participants and award winners!

post_text: The Wyomissing Area Mini-THON committee is proud to announce that through this year’s event Wyomissing Area raised $51,119.63 for Four Diamonds. Thanks to the creative and dedicated planning of the Mini-THON committee and the overwhelming generosity of our community, we are able to help support families as they fight their battles with pediatric cancer. The Mini-THON event was a wonderful success and we could not have done it without the support of faculty, staff, parents, and community members. Thank you again to those that donated to the cause, to the Mini-THON committee for this special experience for our students and community, and to the Mini-THON advisor Ms. Haubrich whose passion and commitment to the cause and to our students is integral in the success of Mini-THON each year. We are so very grateful for her. Stay tuned for photos, videos, and highlights from the night in the coming days. Wyomissing Area is proud to be #forthecure! #fourdiamonds #FTK

The countdown is over! Wyomissing Area’s Mini-THON is TONIGHT and is open to the public from 7-9PM at the JSHS! Join us for carnival games, inflatable fun, yoga, snacks, raffles, and our new our student-designed, themed experiences (aspiring movie stars, gamers, campers, and astronauts, this is for you!).

The Wyomissing Area Mini-THON has become a legacy for our community; it’s a time to come together in the fight against pediatric cancer.

Help us kick off this annual community event and celebrating raising money ...for the cure!

Those wishing to donate to the cause can do so using the included link to Donor Drive posted in the comments. Thank you so much for your support.

post_text: The members of the Wyomissing Area Chess Team are once again the County Champions as of last Tuesday 2/18. Wilson and Wyomissing Area were both undefeated entering the last week of the season having tied in their dual match the previous week, but Wyomissing Area’s talented and focused team came away with the Championship win. This win makes 7 County Chess Championship titles for Wyomissing Area in the last 10 years. Congratulations to all members of the team, and their coach Mr. Minich.

post_text: During the spring, students in Junior High and Senior High Math Team begin to compete in many different county-wide competitions. Junior High Math Team recently competed in the MATHCOUNTS chapter competition with 15 other schools in Berks County. After a variety of different math tests, Wyomissing Area student Thomas Weller placed in the top 10 out of the 100 students who participated. Additionally, both JH and SH mathletes competed in the AMC math competition. If any students do particularly well on this test, they will advance through the next rounds of the AMC program, and we are currently awaiting results. Congratulations to Thomas, and good luck to all our other mathletes!

Our Wyomissing Area swimmers just finished a successful CPL championship meet on 2/14 and 2/15. Many swimmers had lifetime best swims at this meet. Hannah Hurleman finished 3rd in the 100 fly with a time of 57.50 and 1st in the 100 free with a time of 51.94, and now holds Exeter's school records in both of these events! Additionally, she was a part of the 200 freestyle relay that placed 3rd (1:38.71) and the 400 free relay which placed third (3:34:51) which are both new school records as well.

Hannah deserves tremendous recognition for her success and dedication, along with the other talented members of the swim team. This year’s Wyomissing Area swimmers are:

Josh Cole
Caitlyn DeNapoli
William Fanning
Hannah Focht
Hannah Hurleman
Tanner Maier
Steven Olexy
Catrin Stratton-Brown
James Stratton-Brown
Olivia Tipton

We are proud of all of you!

post_text: Thanks to the organization efforts of Mrs. Les, librarian and Mrs. Frederick, speech-language therapist, WHEC kicked off their “One School One Book” program this week. Every student K-4 and every staff member at the Hills received their very own copy of the book “Fenway and Hattie” by Victoria J. Coe. Everyone will read the same book together for the next month, and in mid-March the book’s author will visit the school and provide two days of workshop style assemblies for all students. The books were provided by our generous PTA and the author visit is sponsored by the Wyomissing Area Education Foundation. The entire school community is very excited to get reading!

post_text: For National Read Aloud Day our Assistant Superintendent Dr. Woodard visited with Mrs. Metzger’s class and read the book: “Melody’s Gift”. This is a special book written by West Reading Elementary principal Dr. Babb, and illustrated by Wyomissing Area’s art teacher Mr. Miller. The class loved the sweet story about feeling special and valued, and they were able to identify the many ways the main character displayed personification. They also enjoyed the beautifully detailed illustrations throughout the story.

post_text: The JSHS Service Club is working on their Canstructure event. They are in the process of collecting canned food items which they will use to construct a structure in the Canstructure competition. Ultimately, all of the collected cans from participating teams will be donated to hungry people in Berks County through Helping Harvest. Thank you to those who have donated cans already- keep them coming! Students are collecting cans in Homeroom through next week at both the JSHS and WREC!

post_text: Mr. Krick’s Algebra I-B students culminated their Beanie Bungee Projects with “Drop Day.” They dropped their beanie attached to a bungee cord from the light booth in the auditorium. We love opportunities to see learning in action. Well done Mr. Krick and Algebra 1-B.

post_text: The HS Mini-THON club hosted a Faculty Game Show fundraiser last night to raise money for the Four Diamonds. Over 30 teachers and administrators from all 3 buildings participated in a fun night of challenges including Perfect Pairs, Heads Up, Blindfolded Musical Chairs, and Faculty Feud. After a night of entertainment and laughter, and thanks to the generous donations of our student, parent, faculty, and community guests, the event raised over $2,200 for the cause. Notable recognition goes to fifth grade student Justice Hardy whose special donation landed him a spot on the 3rd grade teacher team to give them a hand. We are so proud of our Mini-THON committee for all of the work they do to organize these wonderful community events for such a worthwhile cause, and are grateful for their dedicated advisor Ms. Haubrich. She goes above and beyond to provide these memorable events for our students. Thank you to all those who participated and attended. The Spartans are #FTK.

post_text: For the second consecutive year, the Wyomissing Area Junior High School is participating in the “What’s So Cool About Manufacturing” video contest. Eight junior high students were matched with Carpenter Technology to create a 2-3 minute video displaying what is “so cool” about the manufacturing field and why students should be interested in that occupation. The junior high students—Abby Zechman, Lael Diehl, Riley Giblin, Maddie Aikman, Pearl Caldwell, Vanessa Aguay, Lily Caldwell, and Mya Bagenstose—were chosen to compete together as a team with guidance from Mrs. Towne. The girls enjoyed working with the technology, both filming and editing to create their video that will become public on February 26, 2020. Voting for the contest will occur from February 26 to February 28, 2020. Voting is open to the students as well as the public, and with all the hard work the girls have done, they urge everyone to check out and vote for their video during the timeframe at https:// www.whatssocool.org/contests/berks-schuylkill/ and they hope to win the Voter’s Award with your help.

January 28 at 1:32 PM ·

During the 2018 Blue & White party, guests raised their paddles in support of the purchase of Google Expedition kits which include Virtual Reality (VR) and Augmented Reality (AR) goggles. These goggles are being put to great use by teachers in all three school buildings! Thank you to all those who contributed, and stay tuned for the 2020 Blue & White party fund-a-need item in support of the Wyomissing Area School District!

Congratulations to senior, Kylee Loeb, whose artwork was chosen to represent Wyomissing Area at the BCIU Student Artwork Showcase. Kylee’s piece will hang in the boardroom at the BCIU for the duration of the 2020 school year. Congratulations also to the following art students whose work earned a spot in the Yocum Institute for the Art’s Annual Berks County High School Juried Exhibit Show:

* Lydia Altomare
* Katherine Baez
* Reese Dauber
* Lily Harris
* Katie Kaufmann
* Emily Kowalski
* Kylee Loeb
* Leah Mitchell
* Elizabeth Morales-Torres
* Emmerson Piacine
* Ciera Ponton

Special recognition goes to Kylee Loeb for this work as well, which earned 3rd place in the exhibit, and also to Lily Harris, whose work received the Coggins Award for the show! The opening reception for the art exhibit will be on Sunday, January 26 from 2-4pm. The awards ceremony will begin at 2:45. The show will remain open from January 26th through February 9th.

post_text: We would like to express special thanks to Berks Career and Technology Center for hosting many of our teachers on Friday. Teachers had the opportunity to tour the facility to learn about all of the fantastic programs BCTC offers the students of Berks County. The goal of this visit was to raise teacher awareness of these unique opportunities so they can better inform students about the numerous pathways available to successful careers. Teachers found the experience quite enjoyable and were impressed by all of the interesting skills our students are developing through their programs at BCTC.

Mrs. Shomgard and students in our Spanish program would like to express a heartfelt thank you to everyone who participated, helped, and supported their book drive and candle fundraiser for The Superkids Foundation. With your support, they donated over 75 books for the start of their library and raised over $500 dollars that will go directly to the Superkids Foundation's programs of literacy, life skills, and leadership to empower children as heroes in their daily lives. We love when Wyomissing Area gives back and connects with others, and are grateful to Mrs. Shomgard for organizing this unique and special opportunity. The students look forward to continuing their growing friendships with the children in Paraguay.

post_text: Students put their learning into practice for their AP Physics midterm with the Egg Drop Project. They were tasked with building a parachute device that would protect their egg when released from various heights. The catch? They were only allowed to use materials from the provided list to compete the mission! Students took turns trying out their parachutes, and the most successful projects survived the 25 foot drop! This was such an engaging activity and really encouraged students to apply their learning and creativity. Way to go AP Physics and Mr. Nugent!

post_text: Students in the JSHS Public Art Workshop have worked collaboratively with local artist Suzanne Fellows to create a new mural for West Reading. This mural will be located behind Baldwin Brass, in the 600 block of Court Street. This is the first project to be created for Court Street. Students took inspiration for the project from Islamic Geometry, through Suzanne Fellows’ guidance. After studying where these beautiful designs are found and how they are created through geometric processes, the students each created their own design. The students’ designs were made into stencils that were used in the larger mural pattern. The mural was created at school on a polyester material that will be permanently attached to the building later this Spring. Thanks to Baldwin Brass, the West Reading Community Revitalization Foundation and the Wyomissing Area Education Foundation for their support of this project.

post_text: We love opportunities for our Spartans to show all they have learned! The National Geographic Geography Bee is held annually at WREC in December. The questions and rules for competition are set forth by National Geographic. Fifteen 5th and 6th graders were represented in the Bee this year, and 5 finalists answered their first six questions correctly. 6th grader Marley Lang was our champion this year, and now qualifies to take an online test to see if she can advance to the state level of competition. We wish her well!

post_text: Wyomissing Area is so lucky to have motivated and dedicated teachers that work daily to bring learning to life, and to share their knowledge with our students. Recently, our sixth grade students met with Mr. Tony Kunkle, Ms. Kupiszewski's cousin. The students have been following his year in Antarctica and learning about scientific studies at the Amundsen Scott Research Station at the South Pole which pertain to their studies in Earth and Space science. They have studied the layers of the atmosphere and the ozone in the stratosphere. The graphs included were supplied by the scientists at the Admundsen Scott South Pole Station from a weather balloon sent to measure the hole in the ozone layer with assistance from Mr. Kunkle. Thank you so much to Mr. Kunkle and Ms. Kupiszewski for sharing this unique experience with our Spartans.

Senior, Lily Harris, and junior, Emmerson Piacine, earned 2nd and 3rd places respectively for their entries into the YWCA Tri-County Area's art competition, "A Week without Violence." This organization focuses on promoting equality, justice, freedom, peace, and dignity for all.

Well done!

post_text: The JSHS Academic Economics teams finished 1st and 2nd place in the Pennsylvania Stock Market Simulation for SE PA. In this simulation, each team is given a fictitious $100,000 to invest in a variety of investment-grade paper such as stocks, bonds, and mutual funds over a 10-week period. The goal is to see who can grow their asset worth over this time period. It is a great simulation of market forces, and more importantly, the importance of saving and investing in the real world. Joey Anzulewicz won the competition with a 19.6% gain over 10 weeks. The team of Alyssa Martinez, Justice Woomer, and Juan Ruiz placed second with a 19.2% return. Joey invested in the tech sector while Alyssa, Justice and Juan invested in the consumer retail sector of the market. Their teacher, Mr. Hetrich, was on BCTV last night (12/9) discussing features of the game and its value to his students. Below are students Justice Woomer, Nick Willman, Joey Anzulewicz, and Alyssa Martinez.

post_text: Earlier in November, Mrs. Wojciechowski’s 3rd grade class invited former WAHS Graduate, Sgt. Brian Flannery, to be honored for his service to our country. Mrs. Wojo's class spent time during that week to learn about Veterans and their commitment to our country. Sgt. Flannery was a member of our Armed Forces, and he spent time with the third graders sharing his experience in our military. Students read letters of appreciation for and support of his service. They were so excited to learn all about his life in the army. One of the coolest facts we learned was that Sgt. Flannery used to jump out of planes, even at night! It was a wonderful morning spent with Sgt. Flannery, and we even got to meet his daughter who came along for the visit. Mrs. Wojo and her class are hoping to make this a tradition and continue to honor community members who have served.

Thanks for this neat challenge, Mr. Nugent!

post_text: Thank you Riverview Bank for your support of WAEF and our students.
shared_text:
Wyomissing Area Education Foundation
November 13, 2019 at 7:46 PM ·

WAEF was recently awarded $5,000 by Riverview Bank. Pictured here are Stacy Galiano, Commercial Relationship Assistant; Karen Scalese, Branch Manager; Molly McCullough Murrill, WAEF Executive Director; Lauren Zuidema, WAEF Board VP, and Jason Shaffer, Commercial Lender.

Ginger Kunkel, SEVP and Chief Operating Officer for Riverview Bank stated, “As a community bank, nothing is more important to us than supporting the growth and development of the markets we serve.” Added Steve Ehrlich, SEVP and Chief Strategy Officer, “We are especially committed to supporting the efforts of local organizations, such as the Wyomissing Area Education Foundation, that work to enrich the lives of our youth and help to develop our next generation of community leaders.”

WAEF is so pleased that Riverview Bank continues to support us and the work we are doing in partnership with the Wyomissing Area School District! We are honored to be a recipient, and these increased EITC funds from Riverview Bank will greatly impact Wyomissing’s students and faculty.

post_text: Career Day at the JSHS last week was a huge success. Thanks to the excellent planning and coordinating by the PTA Career Day Committee, Mrs. Barletta in the guidance office, and other faculty and staff, our students participated in numerous grade specific activities related to careers and post-secondary planning. Students attended panels and guest speaker presentations in a wide variety of fields, engaged in round table discussions with professionals, visited the career fair, updated their resumes, discussed skills valuable in the workforce, and more. Seniors attended the financial reality fair, supported seniors in our community by making blankets that will be donated, took a personality inventory, and participated in CPR training. With over 100 volunteers and guest speakers, the building was full of learning opportunities last Wednesday and we are so thankful for this experience for our students. #pta #careerday #thankyou #collegeandcareerreadiness

post_text: Every Halloween for the past 15+ years, Mr. Hetrich takes some of his history classes on a spooky but impactful trip, led by candlelight, down to the “crypt” under the stage to discuss the historical origins of Halloween and what happened in and around Salem, Massachusetts in the late-winter – early-fall of 1692. During the Salem Witch Trials, over 150 people were accused by around a dozen girls of being witches and warlocks. Mr. Hetrich and his students discuss the historical circumstances that led to this mass hysteria and then discuss synthesis points in history where mass hysteria pushed society into other outrageous acts of discrimination. Students always enjoy this educational and thematic Halloween tradition.

post_text: On Wednesday, October 30th, several 7th and 8th grade students had the opportunity to visit Carpenter Technology in Reading for the “What’s So Cool About Manufacturing” Video Competition. The students were able to gain an intimate perspective of “What Makes Manufacturing so Cool” by interviewing several employees and taking a close look at the various machines and procedures used to manufacture steel bars and coils. The students will now be taking the hours of footage and interviews to create a video showcasing the company and opportunities available in Manufacturing at Carpenter Technology. In February, the videos will be published for a Viewer’s Choice Award! Keep an eye out for our video and vote for Wyomissing Junior High.

post_text: Students in Miss Tierney‘s AP and Honors statistics classes prepared for their test on bivariate data and linear regression with a skittles lab on Wednesday last week. They collected data and applied concepts such as correlation, linear regression, and analyzing the residual plot to determine if a linear model was appropriate for the data. The hands on experience allowed them to get familiar with using their calculator, and to evaluate the validity of a linear regression model from start to finish.

post_text: Mr. Winson’s 9th grade US history classes took a field trip to the auditorium last week, where they participated in a gallery walk analyzing WWII propaganda posters. They made their own interpretations about the meaning of each poster, then used their iPads or phones to scan QR codes which led them to research the background of each piece of propaganda. The students were engaged and enthusiastic about the activity, and very happy for the opportunity to learn outside of the classroom! Great idea, Mr. Winson!
